{"parse":{"title":"tea party","pageid":189187,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Tea Party}}\n==English==\n{{wp|[[+ (social gathering)|+]]}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Flame, not lame-tea party.wav|a=US}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A semi-formal [[afternoon]] [[social]] [[gathering]] at which [[tea]], [[sandwich]]es and [[cake]]s are served.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2020 July 1|title=Case Studies: Brew Monday|journal=Rail|page=59|text=On January 23, MTR Elizabeth Line held an office-based '''tea party''' at which colleagues were encouraged to donate home-baked goods. It provided staff with an opportunity to take time out of their busy schedules and reminded everyone to take care of their mental health and wellbeing.}}\n# A type of [[imaginative]] [[play]]ing in which [[children]] gather with each other or their [[doll]]s to [[mimic]] having a real tea party or other formal meal, often without any food at all.\n# {{lb|en|figuratively}} An interaction characterized by a high degree of courtesy, delicacy, deference, and avoidance of conflict.\n#: {{synonyms|en|pink tea}}\n#* {{quote-web|en|title=''Groia v. Law Society of Upper Canada'', 2018 SCC 27 |author=Michael Moldaver|url=https://canlii.ca/t/hsb9d|work=CanLII|date=1 June 2018|accessdate=17 April 2021|text=Trials marked by strife, belligerent behaviour, unwarranted personal attacks, and other forms of disruptive and discourteous conduct are antithetical to the peaceful and orderly resolution of disputes we strive to achieve. By the same token, trials are not — nor are they meant to be — '''tea parties'''. {{...}} Care must be taken to ensure that free expression, resolute advocacy and the right of an accused to make full answer and defence are not sacrificed at the altar of civility.}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|semi-formal social gathering}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|茶話會|tr=cháhuàhuì}}, {{t+|cmn|茶會|tr=cháhuì}}\n* Danish: {{t|da|teselskab|n}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|teekutsut}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|thé|m}}, {{t+|fr|dînette|f}}\n* German: {{t|de|Tee-Party|f}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|uzsonna}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|ティーパーティー|tr=tīpātī}}, {{t+|ja|茶会|tr=ちゃかい, chakai}}, {{t|ja|茗醼|tr=めいえん, meien}}, {{t|ja|茗宴|tr=めいえん, meien}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|티파티}}, {{t|ko|다과회(茶菓會)}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|чајанка|f}}\n* Mongolian: {{t|mn|цайны ёслол}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|chá da tarde|m}}, {{t|pt|café da tarde|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|чаепи́тие|n}}, {{t+|ru|чай|m}}, {{t|ru|зва́ный чай|m}}, {{t|ru|ча́шка ча́я|f}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|tebjudning|c}}, {{t+|sv|teceremoni|c}}, {{t+|sv|te|n}}\n* Tamil: {{t|ta|தேநீர் விருந்து}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|tiệc trà}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|imaginary meal among children}}\n* Danish: {{t|da|teselskab|n}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|leikkiruokailu}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|dinette|f}}, {{t+|fr|dînette|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|chá de bonecas|m}}, {{t|pt|festa do chá|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{l|en|coffee morning}}\n* {{l|en|tea garden}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Lexico}}\n\n{{C|en|Meals|Parties|Tea}}"}}